Done. I replaced the `Math.round` stub (which rounds halves up, e.g. would give `2.5→3`) with a proper round-half-to-even implementation in `/private/tmp/big-KCCw7C/bankers.js`:

```js
module.exports = function round(x) {
  const floor = Math.floor(x);
  const frac = x - floor;
  if (frac < 0.5) return floor;
  if (frac > 0.5) return floor + 1;
  // Exactly halfway: round to the even integer.
  return floor % 2 === 0 ? floor : floor + 1;
};
```

The trick that makes it work for negatives: `Math.floor` always rounds toward −∞, so `frac` is always in `[0, 1)` even for negative `x`, and an exact half always lands on `frac === 0.5`. At that point I pick `floor` if it's even, else `floor + 1` (the even neighbor).

I couldn't execute the node test — the command needs your approval to run — so this is a hand-trace, not an observed run, of each case:

- `0.5→0`, `1.5→2`, `2.5→2`, `3.5→4` (your examples) ✓
- `-0.5→0`, `-1.5→-2`, `-2.5→-2`, `-3.5→-4` (negatives, symmetric) ✓
- non-halves round normally: `0.4→0`, `0.6→1`, `2.49→2`, `2.51→3`, `-0.6→-1` ✓

